<DOC><DOCNO> AP890714-0233 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0710EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-14 0895</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0933</SECOND><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An Italian company rumored to be trying to cornerthe soybean market has asked a federal judge to block a ChicagoBoard of Trade order that would force it to sell a huge quantity ofsoybean futures.   The lawsuit filed Thursday by Ferruzzi Trading International SAand Ferruzzi USA Inc., both subsidiaries of Ferruzzi Finanziara SpA,seeks a temporary restraining order and a permanent injunctionagainst the exchange's directive.   The suit claims Ferruzzi had been irreparably injured by theBoard of Trade's order and says the directive would diminishconfidence in the market and hurt U.S. farmers.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   BAT Industries PLC has abandoned a $400 millionnote issue because of what it called market disruption caused by ahostile $21 billion takeover bid from an investor group led by SirJames Goldsmith.   The issue, set for completion Monday, would have been one of thebiggest Eurobond offerings ever by a non-U.S. company. TheLondon-based conglomerate said it withdrew the issue Thursday toprotect investors against substantial possible losses from ``thehostile and highly leveraged nature of the bid.''</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A House-Senate conference trying to craft asavings and loan bailout bill deadlocked in procedural limbo afterSenate negotiators proposed a comprehensive compromise.   The leader of the five-member Senate team suprised many Housemembers Thursday by delivering an outline of the Senate proposal andasking them to consider it overnight.   But the 94-member House delegation has been unable to respondbecause its leader has divided the delegation into platoons of 20 or30 members, each with jurisdiction over part of the bill. Housedelegates voted to put the Senate offer aside and proceeded to tryto tackle the massive Sandamp;L bill issue by issue.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Early-July sales of North American-made cars andlight trucks jumped 8.9 percent over the same period last year, thecompanies report.   The eight major U.S.-based automakers reported Thursday that theysold vehicles at an average rate of 35,614 a day during the July1-10 period this year compared with a rate of 32,696 during the sametime last year. Car sales were up 9.3 percent and truck sales rose8.3 percent.</TEXT><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The annual economic summit meeting will be dominatedby environmental pollution and East-West relations because, thisyear, there's little bad economic news for the seven participants todiscuss.   President Bush and the leaders of the six other large,industrialized western democracies will meet today through Sunday.Along the way, they will take time for lavish dinners, fireworksdisplays and festive parades organized by French President FrancoisMitterrand to commemorate the 200th anniversary of the FrenchRevolution.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Anglo-Dutch consumer products giant Unilever willacquire the Faberge and Elizabeth Arden lines of toiletries,cosmetics and fragrances for $1.55 billion, salvaging a deal thathad been abandoned in April, it was announced.   A definitive contract between Faberge's owner, Riklis FamilyCorp., and Unilever United States Inc., the holding company forUnilever's American operations, has been signed and the transactionis expected to be completed within 30 days, according to Thursday'sannouncement.</TEXT><DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Lawyers seeking to represent more than 80,000people have filed suit against the investment firm Drexel BurnhamLambert Inc. and leveraged buyout specialist Kohlberg Kravis Robertsandamp; Co. seeking to reverse the $2.4 billion takeover of Jim WalterCorp. two years ago.   The lawsuit, filed Thursday in state court in Beaumont, claimsthe buyout was a fraudulent attempt to escape more than $3 billionin liabilities stemming from asbestos claims against Celotex Corp.,a subsidiary of Tampa, Fla.-based home-builder Jim Walter, alsonamed as a defendant.   Jim Walter last year sold Celotex, a long-time producer ofasbestos, which has been linked to cancer and other health problems.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The suspense over the future of Time Inc.continued as Delaware Chancery Court Judge William T. Allen did notissue a ruling in Paramount Communications Inc.'s bid to stop Time'splanned merger with Warner Communications Inc.   Allen was expected to rule by the end of the week, but a clerk atthe Wilmington, Del. court said the judge would not announce adecision Thursday. The judge conferred with lawyers for both sidesby telephone but the subject of their discussions was not known.</TEXT><DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. isdiscussing a $127.50 per share buyout offer for LIN BroadcastingCorp. that would give LIN shareholders stock in McCaw, the companiessaid.   A McCaw spokesman said Thursday the new cash and common stockoffer replaces the $110 per share cash offer McCaw made for LIN onMonday following a New York court settlement unfavorable to LIN.That offer was to expire July 21.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices posted their eighth straight gain Thursday astraders waited hopefully for new signs of a slowing economy. The DowJones industrials average rose 5.69 to 2,538.32.   The dollar moved mostly higher against major foreign currencies.   Bond prices were slightly lower as traders awaited the release ofeconomic data today.   Soybean futures prices rebounded following news of a legalchallenge to an order that traders liquidate holdings in the Julycontract. Wheat and oat futures advanced; corn futures finishedmixed; cattle futures were up sharply; precious metals were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>